MY opinion:

I find it unlikely, but not impossible, that someone with
Shakespeare's education, known acquaintances, and apparent
experience of life could have penned the works attributed
to him, at least without a great deal of help.

From my examination of the facts surrounding Marlowe's
death, it seems clear that the most likely explanation for
those people to have met at Deptford that day was to make
it *appear* that he was dead, whereas he did in fact survive.

It is possible to interpret the 'Shakspeare' monument at
Stratford as saying that Marlowe was commemorated in it too,
and the probability of this hidden meaning having occurred
by chance is infinitesimally small.

Regardless of what the history books tell me, therefore, it
is my considered opinion that Marlowe survived 1593, and
played a major part in writing the works normally attributed
solely to Shakespeare.

A question:

Is this explanation of why I find myself believing what I
do reflected in any way either in the tired old Stratford-
ian garbage trotted out here by Bob Grumman or, infinite-
ly more disgusting, the 'Holocaust-denial' vomit spewed
out by the likes of McCrea and his ilk?

