When I was in Portland in 2001, Dr. Steven Steffens, Ph.D, gave a talk
that has some bearing on this discussion. It was titled &quot;Psychological
Contributions to the Study of Creativity: The Requirements for
Greatness.&quot;

The essence of the presentation had to do with statistical analysis of
how greatness in artists developed and matured and showed strong
consistentcy throughout history. (Which I'll get to in a second).

Grumman, as usual, misstates a core Anti Stratfordian belief, which
Peter refines more precisely. I believe it is a straw man argument. I
certainly and many I know would never argue that &quot;genius&quot; can't flower
independently of formal study or out of self exploration and discovery.
That would be absurd. History is replete with those who did precisely
that.

The problem as I perceive our position is two fold. The biographical
life and the art do not seem to match. This was more Peter's
orientation. Which dovetails with the more central issue, where is any
EVIDENCE, even a little, of the kinds of associations such a self
motivated life would provide? (This was Price's position which has been
vehemently fought and denied here and elsewhere.) Such as evidence of
access or ownership of BOOKS. Shakespeare referred to over 2000 Bible
verses. Did he just &quot;pop in&quot; to a friends house to look at a Bible (or
many versions apparently) when needed? &quot;Oh, I need this verse, let me
saunter to ___'s house to refresh my memory. Or a little Holinshed.
Maybe that French guy, Belleforest.&quot;

Back to Steffens. In studying great master artists across the board,
several strands of development stood out. First, there was an
ENVIRONMENT that supported the artist's nurturance. And a long period
of APPRENTICESHIP. The craft dod not spring out of &quot;thin air&quot;. Contrary
to popular belief. Mozart worked long and hard to develop his talent,
even though being a prodigy. Secondly, the first appearance of a
&quot;Master&quot; work took about ten years to blossom after this period of
apprenticeship. True for Mozart and most others.

So according to this model, Venus and Adonis could not have been a
&quot;starter&quot; piece. There had to have been some period of gestation,
juvenalia, development before such a work could emerge.

Finally, in the literary field, great writers almost always early on
had a very strong asociation with BOOKS. They played a huge role in
their early years.

So this kind of off kilter characterization is again brought up. If you
read Twain's critique, who WAS a great writer himself (unless Grumman
declares otherwise in his usual hubris), it was the seamless use of
language and metaphor that spoke to Twain of some experiential
association with the subjects in the works, not the level of formal
schooling or not. Twain himself is a prime example of the model,
spending years as a printer and developing writer (doing snippets for
local papers) before his art began to show. Where was the * REAL
evidence* for these associations for Shakespeare, somewhere, somehow,
instead of the constant, prosaic evidence in the life of money, money,
money.

Threaten someone's life(Wayte)- most likely money involved somewhere
Hoard grain-money
Buy big house-money
Only letter about-you guessed it-BORROWING MONEY
One of Best friends-MONEY LENDER
Lawsuit over-LENDING MONEY

I didn't say this before, but one aspect of the disingenuousness of
current Strat biography is that there is **far** more evidence to point
to Will as a money lender than the single name that allows those to
conjecture a complete period of life as a member of the Catholic
Underground. Why do you suppose this evidentiary line is not followed
as a part of &quot;imaginative biography?&quot; If there is going to be all this
lumping of &quot;Anti's&quot; together, then must you all answer as well for the
egregious antics of your far better known brethren?

If I take a more conservative approach, which I am willing to do, then
some of these points, especially the research Steffens cited, *might*
be taken into account as part of the considerattion of the subject.

And Tom, I applaud in a limited fashion your perspective on the
Holocaust Denial piece. But please tell me, and this has been gone over
ad nauseum, where do Holocaust Deniers gain the same stature of
intellectual currency among prominent artists and intellectuals
thoughout recent history as those who see a problem with authorship
attribution? We can disagree strongly on the nature of the evidence. Or
that there is a problem, but I do not think the situations are
analagous.

The Kennedy assassination is more apt. People disagree strongly but
many people of high regard have cause for doubt in the official
version. Are they &quot;demented&quot; for having those doubts? Are their though
processes &quot;irrational&quot;? (Just for the record, my belief is the
forensics as known suppport a single shooter from the sixth floor. But
whether this rules out any conspiracy _completely_ is a different
story, for many reasons.)

Ken Kaplan

